          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>What does the body primarily rely on to switch between carbohydrate, lipid, and protein fuel sources during different metabolic states?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Hormonal signals</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Hormones such as insulin and glucagon orchestrate which fuel pathway dominates — insulin promotes glucose uptake and storage in the fed state, while glucagon triggers glycogenolysis and lipolysis during fasting.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Voluntary dietary choices made in real time</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Dietary intake determines what substrates are available, but the moment-to-moment switching between fuel sources is governed by hormonal signals, not conscious choice.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Changes in core body temperature</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Body temperature influences metabolic rate but does not determine which fuel source the body selects. Hormonal signals direct the switch between carbohydrate, lipid, and protein metabolism.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Fluctuations in blood oxygen levels</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Oxygen availability affects aerobic versus anaerobic metabolism, but the integration of carbohydrate, lipid, and protein pathways is controlled by hormonal signals such as insulin and glucagon.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The video states clearly that 'the body switches between fuel sources based on hormonal signals.' Hormones like insulin and glucagon are the key regulators of metabolic integration."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The video emphasises that hormonal signals — particularly insulin and glucagon — are the master regulators that determine which fuel pathway is active at any given time."
                }
              ],
