          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>According to Peter Mitchell's chemiosmotic hypothesis, how is energy stored for ATP synthesis in mitochondria?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>As a high-energy chemical intermediate</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This was the prevailing theory before Mitchell. He challenged it and demonstrated that no such intermediate exists — the energy is stored as a proton gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>As an electrochemical gradient of protons across the inner mitochondrial membrane</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Mitchell proposed that Complexes I, III, and IV pump protons across the inner mitochondrial membrane, creating a gradient. ATP synthase then harnesses this proton-motive force to manufacture ATP.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>As thermal energy within the mitochondrial matrix</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>While some energy is inevitably lost as heat, Mitchell showed that the usable energy driving ATP synthesis is stored as an electrochemical proton gradient, not as thermal energy.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>As covalent bonds within the electron carriers NADH and FADH₂</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>NADH and FADH₂ donate electrons to the transport chain, but the energy that directly drives ATP synthesis is stored as a proton gradient — the central insight of the chemiosmotic hypothesis.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The video explains that Mitchell proposed energy is stored as 'a gradient of protons across the inner mitochondrial membrane,' overturning the old chemical intermediate theory. This proton-motive force powers ATP synthase."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Excellent. Mitchell's chemiosmotic hypothesis — that biological energy is stored as an electrochemical gradient rather than a chemical intermediate — earned him the 1978 Nobel Prize and is considered one of the most elegant ideas in biology."
                }
              ],
